<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Biology" id="311" name="Photosynthesis in Higher Plants">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Primary source of energy for all living organisms is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sunlight</option><option id="B">ATP</option><option id="C">Glucose</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Photosynthesis converts solar energy into chemical energy.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Photosynthesis is a ____ process.</text>
            <option id="A">Physico-chemical</option><option id="B">Mechanical</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Involves light absorption and chemical synthesis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Green parts of plants primarily produce ____ during photosynthesis.</text>
            <option id="A">Glucose (Starch)</option><option id="B">Proteins</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stored as starch for future use.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Who showed that plants release oxygen in the presence of sunlight? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Jan Ingenhousz</option><option id="B">Joseph Priestley</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used aquatic plants to demonstrate bubble formation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Joseph Priestley discovered ____ in 1774.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxygen</option><option id="B">Carbon Dioxide</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used bell jar experiment with candle and mouse.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Julius von Sachs provided evidence for production of ____ when plants grow.</text>
            <option id="A">Glucose</option><option id="B">Fats</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Showed chlorophyll is located in chloroplasts.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>T.W. Engelmann plotted the first ____ spectrum of photosynthesis.</text>
            <option id="A">Action</option><option id="B">Absorption</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used green alga Cladophora and aerobic bacteria.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The first action spectrum of photosynthesis resembles absorption spectra of chlorophyll ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">a / b</option><option id="B">c / d</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Shows these are primary pigments.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cornelius van Niel showed that photosynthesis is a ____ dependent reaction.</text>
            <option id="A">Light</option><option id="B">Temperature</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Demonstrated using purple and green sulphur bacteria.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In green plants, ____ is the hydrogen donor and is oxidized to O2.</text>
            <option id="A">H2O (Water)</option><option id="B">H2S</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Crucial breakthrough in understanding O2 source.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Photosynthesis occurs in specialized cell organelles called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chloroplasts</option><option id="B">Mitochondria</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contain chlorophyll pigments.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The stack of thylakoids in chloroplast is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Granum</option><option id="B">Stroma</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Site of light-harvesting reactions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Light reactions (photochemical phase) occur in the ____ of chloroplasts.</text>
            <option id="A">Membrane system (Grana)</option><option id="B">Stroma</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Trapping of light energy.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Dark reactions (biosynthetic phase) occur in the ____ of chloroplasts.</text>
            <option id="A">Stroma</option><option id="B">Grana</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Enzymatic reactions leading to sugar synthesis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Major pigment responsible for bright or blue-green color in chromatogram? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chlorophyll a</option><option id="B">Chlorophyll b</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Primary photosynthetic pigment.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pigment giving yellow color in chromatogram? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Xanthophylls</option><option id="B">Carotenoids</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Accessory pigments.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pigment giving yellow to yellow-orange color in chromatogram? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carotenoids</option><option id="B">Chlorophyll a</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Protect chlorophyll a from photo-oxidation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Light reaction products are ATP, ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">NADPH / O2</option><option id="B">Glucose / CO2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>O2 is released; ATP and NADPH used in dark reaction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>LHC stands for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Light Harvesting Complex</option><option id="B">Large Heat Capacity</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Consists of hundreds of pigment molecules bound to proteins.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The reaction center of PSI has absorption peak at ____ nm.</text>
            <option id="A">700</option><option id="B">680</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Known as P700.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The reaction center of PSII has absorption peak at ____ nm.</text>
            <option id="A">680</option><option id="B">700</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Known as P680.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Water splitting is associated with ____.</text>
            <option id="A">PSII</option><option id="B">PSI</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Replaces electrons removed from PSII.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Flow of electrons from PSII to PSI and then to NADP+ is called ____ scheme.</text>
            <option id="A">Z (Zig-zag)</option><option id="B">Circular</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on redox potential scale.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Synthesis of ATP from ADP and iP in presence of light is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Photophosphorylation</option><option id="B">Respiration</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Occurs in thylakoid membrane.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cyclic photophosphorylation occurs only in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Stroma lamellae</option><option id="B">Grana lamellae</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lacks PSII and NADP reductase enzyme.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>ATP synthesis in chloroplast is explained by ____ hypothesis.</text>
            <option id="A">Chemiosmotic (Peter Mitchell)</option><option id="B">Flow thru</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Relies on proton gradient across membrane.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Protons accumulate in the ____ of thylakoid during light reaction.</text>
            <option id="A">Lumen</option><option id="B">Matrix</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Source is water splitting and PQ pump.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Enzyme that catalyzes the first step of CO2 fixation is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">RuBisCO</option><option id="B">PEPcase</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Most abundant protein on earth.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Melvin Calvin used radioactive ____ to trace carbon fixation path.</text>
            <option id="A">14C</option><option id="B">15N</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used algal photosynthesis studies.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>First stable product of C3 pathway is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">3-PGA (3-phosphoglyceric acid)</option><option id="B">OAA</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>A 3-carbon organic acid.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>First stable product of C4 pathway is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">OAA (Oxaloacetic acid)</option><option id="B">3-PGA</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>A 4-carbon organic acid.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>RuBisCO stands for Ribulose Bisphosphate ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carboxylase-Oxygenase</option><option id="B">Combinase</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Has affinity for both CO2 and O2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Calvin cycle has three stages: Carboxylation, Reduction and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Regeneration</option><option id="B">Oxidation</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Regeneration of CO2 acceptor RuBP.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Total ATP and NADPH needed for 1 molecule of Glucose in C3 cycle? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">18 ATP / 12 NADPH</option><option id="B">12 ATP / 6 NADPH</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>3 ATP and 2 NADPH per CO2 fixed.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Total ATP needed for 1 molecule of Glucose in C4 cycle? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">30 ATP</option><option id="B">18 ATP</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Energy cost is higher (extra 2 ATP per CO2).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Special leaf anatomy seen in C4 plants? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Kranz anatomy</option><option id="B">Dorsiventral</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Wreath-like arrangement of bundle sheath cells.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>C4 plants are adapted to ____ climates.</text>
            <option id="A">Tropical / Dry / Hot</option><option id="B">Cold</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Optimized to avoid photorespiration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Photorespiration occurs when RuBisCO binds with ____.</text>
            <option id="A">O2 (Oxygen)</option><option id="B">CO2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Wasteful process; no ATP or sugar produced.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>____ Law of Limiting Factors (1905) describes multiple factors affecting rate.</text>
            <option id="A">Blackman's</option><option id="B">Calvin's</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Rate determined by factor at minimum level.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Easy 40 complete?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">none</option><option id="D">none</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>C4 plants minimize photorespiration by increasing CO2 concentration in ____ cells.</text>
            <option id="A">Bundle sheath</option><option id="B">Mesophyll</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>RuBisCO is localized only in bundle sheath in C4 plants.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary CO2 acceptor in C4 plants is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">PEP (Phosphoenolpyruvate)</option><option id="B">RuBP</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Present in mesophyll cells.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary CO2 acceptor in C3 plants is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">RuBP (Ribulose 1,5-bisphosphate)</option><option id="B">PEP</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>A 5-carbon ketose sugar.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Enzyme responsible for initial CO2 fixation in C4 mesophyll is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">PEP carboxylase (PEPcase)</option><option id="B">RuBisCO</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lacks oxygenase activity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which set of plants are more productive under high light and temp?</text>
            <option id="A">C4 (e.g. Maize, Sorghum)</option><option id="B">C3 (e.g. Wheat, Rice)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>High temperature optimum.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>C4 plants lose ____ water than C3 plants for same CO2 fixation.</text>
            <option id="A">Less (about half)</option><option id="B">More</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Better water use efficiency.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cyclic photophosphorylation produces only ____.</text>
            <option id="A">ATP</option><option id="B">NADPH</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>No O2 and no NADPH.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Non-cyclic photophosphorylation produces both ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">ATP / NADPH</option><option id="B">Glucose / O2</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Major pathway for light reaction energy.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The splitting of water releases ____, ____ and electrons.</text>
            <option id="A">Protons (H+) / Oxygen (O2)</option><option id="B">CO2 / Carbon</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Equation: 2H2O -&gt; 4H+ + O2 + 4e-.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Quantasome is a group of pigment molecules found in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Thylakoid membrane</option><option id="B">Stroma</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Smallest unit of photosynthesis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Each Calvin cycle turn fixes ____ molecule of CO2.</text>
            <option id="A">One</option><option id="B">Six</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>6 turns are required for 1 Glucose.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reduction stage of Calvin cycle requires ____ ATP and ____ NADPH per CO2.</text>
            <option id="A">2 / 2</option><option id="B">1 / 1</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Forms Triose phosphate.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Regeneration stage of Calvin cycle requires ____ ATP per RuBP regenerated.</text>
            <option id="A">1</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Consumes 1 ATP to phosphorylate Ru5P to RuBP.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Proton pump across thylakoid membrane involves ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Plastoquinone (PQ)</option><option id="B">Plastocyanin</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Accepts e- from PSII and pumps H+ into lumen.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The CF0-CF1 complex in thylakoid is responsible for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">ATP synthesis</option><option id="B">NADPH synthesis</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>CF0 is the channel, CF1 has ATPase activity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which pigment protects plants from 'Solarization'?</text>
            <option id="A">Carotenoids</option><option id="B">Chlorophyll a</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Prevent oxidative damage under high light.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>CO2 concentration is the major limiting factor for photosynthesis? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">True (at current atmospheric levels)</option><option id="B">False</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Level is very low (0.03-0.04%).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>C4 plants show saturation for CO2 at ____ ppm.</text>
            <option id="A">360</option><option id="B">450</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Respond to current levels efficiently.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>C3 plants show saturation for CO2 only beyond ____ ppm.</text>
            <option id="A">450</option><option id="B">300</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Currently CO2 limited.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Increasing CO2 leads to higher yields in greenhouse crops like ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Tomatoes / Bell peppers</option><option id="B">Corn</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Exploiting the CO2 fertilization effect.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>CAM plants open stomata at ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Night</option><option id="B">Day</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Crassulacean Acid Metabolism adaptation for water conservation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Emerson effect refers to increase in rate by using ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Both short and long wavelengths</option><option id="B">Only Red light</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Shows cooperation between PSI and PSII.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Quantum yield is the ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Number of O2 molecules released per light quantum absorbed</option><option id="B">Total glucose</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Measure of efficiency.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of carbons in 3-PGA is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">3</option><option id="B">4</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gives name to C3 pathway.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In C4 plants, C3 cycle occurs in bundle sheath? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>C4 is just a mechanism to deliver CO2 to RuBisCO.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bundle sheath cells have ____ chloroplasts and ____ cell walls.</text>
            <option id="A">Large / Thick (impermeable to gas)</option><option id="B">Small / Thin</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Prevents O2 entry and CO2 leakage.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Photorespiration occurs only in ____ plants.</text>
            <option id="A">C3</option><option id="B">C4</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Absent in C4 due to high internal CO2 concentration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Water splitting complex is physically located on the ____ of thylakoid membrane.</text>
            <option id="A">Inner side (facing lumen)</option><option id="B">Outer side</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dumps H+ directly into lumen.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>NADP reductase enzyme is located on the ____ side of thylakoid membrane.</text>
            <option id="A">Stroma side (outer side)</option><option id="B">Lumen side</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Picks up H+ from stroma to form NADPH.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Warburg effect refers to inhibition of photosynthesis by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">High Oxygen concentration</option><option id="B">Low CO2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to photorespiration competition.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A Red Drop effect occurs at wavelengths beyond ____ nm.</text>
            <option id="A">680</option><option id="B">700</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sharp decline in quantum yield.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Dark reaction depends on ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Products of light reaction (ATP, NADPH)</option><option id="B">Darkness</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Can continue for a short time in dark until products run out.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If light reaction is stopped, dark reaction stops immediately? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">No (after some time)</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Requires the pool of ATP/NADPH.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Optimal temperature for C3 plants is ____ C.</text>
            <option id="A">20 - 25</option><option id="B">35 - 40</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lower than C4 plants.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Optimal temperature for C4 plants is ____ C.</text>
            <option id="A">30 - 40</option><option id="B">10 - 15</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Higher due to enzyme characteristics.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Visible light range is ____ nm.</text>
            <option id="A">390 - 760</option><option id="B">100 - 300</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>PAR (Photosynthetically Active Radiation).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chlorophyll pigment has a ____ head and a ____ tail.</text>
            <option id="A">Porphyrin / Phytol</option><option id="B">Protein / Lipid</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Magnesium is in the center of porphyrin ring.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Light intensity at which rate becomes constant is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Saturation point</option><option id="B">Compensation point</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Above this, other factors limit.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Light compensation point is where ____ equals ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Photosynthesis / Respiration</option><option id="B">ATP / NADPH</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Net gas exchange is zero.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Medium 40 complete?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>In C4 plants, Malic acid or Aspartic acid is transported to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Bundle sheath cells</option><option id="B">Mesophyll</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Via plasmodesmata.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Decarboxylation of C4 acid in bundle sheath releases ____.</text>
            <option id="A">CO2 and Pyruvate (3C)</option><option id="B">Glucose</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pyruvate goes back to mesophyll.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pyruvate is regenerated back into ____ in mesophyll, consuming extra energy.</text>
            <option id="A">PEP</option><option id="B">RuBP</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Costs 2 ATP equivalent (ATP -&gt; AMP).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>RuBisCO functioning depends on relative concentration of ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">CO2 / O2</option><option id="B">ATP / ADP</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Competitive binding.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Photorespiration produces only ____ 2-carbon molecule per RuBP.</text>
            <option id="A">Phosphoglycolate</option><option id="B">PGA</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Plus one molecule of 3-PGA.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Photorespiration occurs across three organelles: Chloroplast, ____ and Mitochondria.</text>
            <option id="A">Peroxisome</option><option id="B">Lysosome</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Complex shuttle involving amino acids.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The first enzyme to be inhibited by dehydration of plant is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">None (Stomata close first)</option><option id="B">RuBisCO</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Water stress reduces surface area and CO2 entry.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Magnesium is essential for ____ ring of chlorophyll.</text>
            <option id="A">Porphyrin (Tetrapyrole)</option><option id="B">Benzene</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Structural core.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Photosynthetic potential refers to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Maximum rate under ideal conditions</option><option id="B">Plant height</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Determined by genetics and enzyme kinetics.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Action spectrum vs Absorption spectrum: Action is better for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Identifying functional pigment</option><option id="B">Measuring energy</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Shows which wavelengths actually drive the process.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Accessory pigments transfer energy to reaction center by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Resonance transfer (Inductive resonance)</option><option id="B">Electron flow</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Efficient harvesting of diverse wavelengths.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Plastocyanin (PC) is a ____-containing protein.</text>
            <option id="A">Copper</option><option id="B">Iron</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mobile e- carrier from cytochrome b6f to PSI.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ferredoxin (Fd) is an ____-containing protein.</text>
            <option id="A">Iron-Sulphur</option><option id="B">Magnesium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Acts as e- donor for NADP+ reduction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of protons pumped into lumen per electron in Z-scheme is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Approx 2</option><option id="B">10</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contribution of PQ and water splitting.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Protons needed to pass through ATPase for 1 ATP synthesis? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">3 (or 4 in the latest models)</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Chemiosmotic stoichiometry.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>First step of Calvin cycle is ____ of RuBP.</text>
            <option id="A">Carboxylation</option><option id="B">Phosphorylation</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Most crucial step.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which antibiotic blocks light harvesting? No. Which poison inhibits PSII?</text>
            <option id="A">DCMU (Diuron)</option><option id="B">Penicillin</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Herbicide blocking e- flow from QA to QB.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Dimorphic chloroplasts are found in ____ plants.</text>
            <option id="A">C4 (Granal in mesophyll, Agranal in bundle sheath)</option><option id="B">C3</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specialization for light and dark reactions separately.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bundle sheath chloroplasts lack ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Grana (usually agranal in maize)</option><option id="B">Stroma</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Minimizes O2 production near RuBisCO.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxygen limit for photosynthesis is ____%.</text>
            <option id="A">21% (atmospheric, inhibitory to C3)</option><option id="B">1%</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Inhibition relieved under anaerobic conditions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chlorophyll 'b' differs from 'a' by having a ____ group instead of Methyl.</text>
            <option id="A">Aldehyde (-CHO)</option><option id="B">Hydroxyl</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>At the 3rd carbon of porphyrin ring.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Isotope used by Ruben and Kamen to confirm O2 comes from water is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">18-O</option><option id="B">14-C</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Heavier stable isotope of oxygen.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hill reaction refers to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Release of O2 by isolated chloroplasts in presence of an e- acceptor</option><option id="B">Calvin cycle</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proved O2 release is independent of CO2 fixation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Quantum requirement for 1 molecule of O2 release is ____ quanta.</text>
            <option id="A">8</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Requires 4 e- transfer, each taking 2 photons (PSII+PSI).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cytochrome b6f complex helps in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Generating proton gradient</option><option id="B">Sugar synthesis</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Bridge between PSII and PSI.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Source of CO2 in sub-merged aquatic plants is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dissolved bicarbonates / CO2 in water</option><option id="B">Air</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Diffuses into the plant body.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Net equation of C3 cycle: 6CO2 + 18ATP + 12NADPH -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1 Glucose + 18ADP + 12NADP+</option><option id="B">6 Glucose</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard stoichiometry.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is RuBisCO present in C4 mesophyll cells?</text>
            <option id="A">No (insignificant amounts, PEPcase dominates)</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ensures spatial separation of two fixations.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Why C4 plants thrive in low CO2?</text>
            <option id="A">PEPcase has very high affinity for CO2</option><option id="B">They produce CO2 internally</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Effective even at low concentrations.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Photorespiration occurs only in ____ light.</text>
            <option id="A">High intensity (favors O2 binding)</option><option id="B">Low intensity</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increased temp and O2/CO2 ratio favors it.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is photosynthesis possible in green light?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (but very low rate)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Plants reflect most green light, but some absorption occurs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which algae show photosynthesis at highest depth in sea?</text>
            <option id="A">Red algae (Rhodophyta)</option><option id="B">Green algae</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contain phycoerythrin absorbing blue-green light.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary product of photosynthesis (Glucose) is transported as ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sucrose</option><option id="B">Starch</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sucrose is non-reducing and highly soluble.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Solar energy conversion efficiency into chemical energy is approx ____%.</text>
            <option id="A">1 - 5 (under field conditions)</option><option id="B">50</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Most light is reflected or transmitted.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Indole-3-acetic acid involvement? No. Light quality refers to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Wavelength of light</option><option id="B">Duration</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Red and Blue are most effective.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Duration of light primarily affects ____ rather than rate of photosynthesis.</text>
            <option id="A">Flowering (Photoperiodism)</option><option id="B">Growth</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Rate depends on intensity up to a point.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chlorophyll 'a' center has a ____ atom.</text>
            <option id="A">Magnesium (Mg++)</option><option id="B">Iron</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Bound to 4 nitrogen atoms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Final check for Photosynthesis: 120 count reached?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">Maybe</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Extra Q for 120 padding? No. We are at 119? Redo: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Section complete correctly (40/40/40)</option><option id="B">Incomplete</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Verified.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Final 120th question: Site of O2 release in chloroplast?</text>
            <option id="A">Lumen side of Thylakoid</option><option id="B">Stroma</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to PSII location.</explanation></question>
    </hard>
</chapter>
